This paper deals with the problem of face hallucination using a multi-scale generative adversarial network (GAN) architecture optimized for face verification. The paper proposes a novel discriminator that learns to discriminate different identities while distinguishing fake generated HR face images from their ground truth images. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper employs a perceptual similarity loss, which indicates that it may also belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories. Finally, the use of GANs suggests that the paper may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category.
